BikeBandit is a motorcycle parts superstore retailer founded in 1999 by Ken Wahlster.   The company sells motorcycle parts, apparel, and accessories through an online store.<ref name="incmagazine">{{cite web|title=BikeBandit.com|url=http://www.inc.com/profile/bikebanditcom|publisher=Inc. Magazine|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref>
==Overview ==

BikeBandit is an online retailer of motorcycle parts and accessories with product offerings for street motorcycles, cruisers, ATVs and snowmobiles.  The company was founded in 1999 by CEO Ken Wahlster.<ref name="dealernews" /> The company initially operated out of Wahlster<U+2019>s home and later grew to occupy a 107,000 square foot facility shipping 10,000 items per day with a customer base of approximately 700,000. <ref name="dealernews" />  The company is named after <U+201C>Bandit,<U+201D> Wahlster<U+2019>s black [[Labrador Retriever|labrador retriever]]. Images of Bandit are still seen across the BikeBandit website.<ref name="dealernews">{{cite web|title=E-commerce pioneer: BikeBandit's Ken Wahlster|url=http://www.dealernews.com/dealernews/article/e-commerce-pioneer-bikebandits-ken-wahlster|publisher=Dealer News|accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref>

==Operations==

BikeBandit<U+2019>s headquarters are located in [[Otay Mesa, San Diego|Otay Mesa]], a community in the southern section of [[San Diego, California|San Diego, California]].  In this location the company is eligible for tax credits through [[Zoning|zoning]] regulations realized from the San Diego Regional Enterprise Zone (<U+201C>SDREZ<U+201D>) program.<ref>{{cite web|title=San Diego Zone One May 2011 Newsletter|url=http://www.sandiego.gov/economic-development/pdf/sdrezmay2011.pdf|publisher=San Diego Regional Enterprise Zone|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> According to ''[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc. Magazine]]'', the company employs a staff of 70 employees with annual revenues of $35M.<ref name="incmagazine" /><ref name="dealernews" /> In 2013, ''[[U-T San Diego|U-T San Diego]]'' noted BikeBandit as one of seven San Diego firms ranked among the Top 500 Internet Retailers.<ref name="uniontribune">{{cite web|title=7 SD firms among top 500 Internet retailers|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2013/may/06/san-diego-companies-top-500-internet-retailers/#&panel1-5|publisher=Katherine P. Harvey|accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref>  [[ChicagoNow|ChicagoNow]] announced that BikeBandit was to release a mobile app for the ''[[iPhone|iPhone]]'' in early 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Motorcycle App for iPhone|url=http://www.chicagonow.com/motorcycle-sarah/2010/02/new-motorcycle-app-for-iphone/|publisher=Sarah Lahalih|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>

==Products==

BikeBandit sells OEM parts, aftermarket parts, accessories, gear and tires for motorcycles, scooters, ATVs, snowmobiles, and personal watercraft.<ref name="dealernews" />

==Sponsorships & Partnerships==

*Title Sponsor of the 2013 AMA Vintage Motorcycle Days event held on July 19-21 at the [[Mid-Ohio Sports Car Course|Mid-Ohio Sports Car Course]] in [[Lexington, Ohio|Lexington Ohio]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mid-Ohio Sports Car Course - Track Rental - Weekend Club Event Schedule|url=http://www.midohio.com/track-rental/weekend-club-event-schedule|publisher=Mid-Ohio Sports Car Course|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref>
*Title Sponsor of the 2014 AMA Vintage Motorcycle Days event held by the [[American Motorcyclist Association|American Motorcycle Association]] (AMA)<ref name="motorcyclecom">{{cite web|title=BikeBandit.Com Returns As Title Sponsor Of 2014 AMA Vintage Motorcycle Days|url=http://blog.motorcycle.com/2014/04/08/products/bikebandit-com-returns-as-title-sponsor-of-2014-ama-vintage-motorcycle-days/|publisher=Motorcycle.com|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref>
*Sponsor of the 2014 AMA Go Ride Safely! Week, an event held by the American Motorcyclist Association to promote rider responsibility and driver awareness.<ref name="motorcyclecom" />
*Hosted Project Re-Cycle in coordination with ''[[Cycle World|Cycle World Magazine]]''. Project Re-Cycle is a non-profit benefit for the Pediatric Brain Tumor Foundation (PBTF).<ref name="projectrecycle">{{cite web|title=PBTF Wins With Project Re-Cycle<U+2019>s FZ6 Auction|url=http://www.motorcycle-usa.com/1/10058/Motorcycle-Article/PBTF-Wins-With-Project-Re-Cycles-FZ6-Auction.aspx|publisher=Motorcycle USA|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref>

